  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When a buyer purchases a unit, townhouse, or lot in a community titles scheme in Queensland, they are also acquiring a proportional stake in the body corporate. That includes liability for ongoing levies, any special levies currently in effect or pending, and exposure to the financial health of the sinking fund. For sellers, understanding the body corporate position before listing is not optional; it is a basic part of sale preparation that directly affects how confidently buyers can proceed.</p>

      <p>Buyers and their solicitors will conduct a body corporate records search as part of due diligence. What that search returns will shape the offer you receive and the conditions attached to it. Getting ahead of the information rather than waiting for it to surface mid-campaign is a far better position to be in.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Admin fund levies versus sinking fund levies</h2>
      <p>Body corporate contributions are split between two funds, each with a different purpose.</p>

      <p>The administration fund covers day-to-day expenses: building insurance, common area cleaning and maintenance, garden upkeep, management fees, and routine repairs. Admin fund levies are the ongoing operational costs of running the body corporate. They are paid quarterly or annually and are budgeted each year by the body corporate committee. A healthy admin fund has a small positive balance that covers unexpected minor expenses without requiring special contributions.</p>

      <p>The sinking fund covers major capital works: roof replacement, lift repairs, painting of common areas, car park resurfacing, and other large periodic expenses. Sinking fund contributions are supposed to be set at a level that accumulates sufficient reserves for known future expenditure. Queensland law requires body corporates to maintain a ten-year sinking fund forecast, which outlines planned capital works and the contributions required to fund them.</p>

      <p>For sellers, both are relevant but the sinking fund position is typically what buyers scrutinise most carefully, because it signals whether the building is financially prepared for the maintenance it will need.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a special levy is and why it can derail a sale</h2>
      <p>A special levy is an additional contribution levied on lot owners when the body corporate needs to fund a capital expense that is not covered by the sinking fund. Special levies arise because the sinking fund is inadequate (either because it was set too low historically or because the capital works needed are larger than anticipated), because an urgent repair is required, or because the body corporate has resolved to undertake a major improvement.</p>

      <p>For buyers, a current or pending special levy is material information. It represents a known additional financial obligation that was not visible in the advertised levy amounts. A buyer who purchases a unit and then receives a special levy notice for a significant amount shortly after settlement will feel misled, regardless of whether the levy was technically disclosed in the body corporate records. If a special levy is in place or pending at the time you are selling, you should disclose it proactively rather than waiting for it to appear in the body corporate search, which typically happens in the conditional period and can create renegotiation pressure at the worst possible time in the campaign.</p>

      <p>A pending special levy does not necessarily kill a sale. Buyers can and do factor known levies into their offer. What causes campaigns to fall over is the discovery of a special levy mid-campaign that the seller knew about and did not mention, because it creates a trust problem that extends to every other aspect of the transaction.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a healthy versus an unhealthy sinking fund looks like</h2>
      <p>Buyers purchasing strata property in Brisbane's inner east have become increasingly attentive to sinking fund health, particularly in older buildings where capital expenditure is more likely. A healthy sinking fund is one that has been consistently funded relative to its ten-year plan, with a balance that provides reasonable coverage of near-term planned expenditure without requiring special levies to meet it.</p>

      <p>An underfunded sinking fund is not automatically a problem for a sale, but it requires honest handling. A buyer who understands the body corporate position and is comfortable with it will still proceed; a buyer who discovers a significant sinking fund shortfall in the body corporate records search and was not prepared for it will often respond with a price reduction request or a termination of contract. Sellers in buildings with underfunded sinking funds are better served by being transparent about the position upfront, ideally by having their agent address it in the marketing and by pricing the property to reflect the levy liability buyers will take on.</p>

      <p>The ten-year sinking fund forecast is a public document within the body corporate records and any buyer's solicitor will examine it. There is no value in sellers attempting to manage information that is fully discoverable in due diligence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to obtain a pre-sale body corporate disclosure certificate</h2>
      <p>Under the Body Corporate and Community Management Act 1997, lot owners are entitled to request a disclosure certificate from the body corporate manager before selling. The disclosure certificate provides a formal summary of the lot's levy position: what is owed, the current levy amounts for both the admin and sinking funds, any special levies in place, and whether the lot is in arrears.</p>

      <p>Sellers are legally required to provide a disclosure certificate to buyers before the contract is signed. Buyers have the right to terminate the contract within 14 days of receiving the disclosure certificate if they are not satisfied with the body corporate's financial position. Understanding your own disclosure certificate before listing means you will not be surprised by anything it contains, and your agent can prepare buyers appropriately before they receive the formal documentation.</p>

      <p>Request the disclosure certificate from your body corporate manager early in the pre-listing process. It typically takes a few business days to prepare and carries a fee. Your conveyancer can also assist with this request and will ensure it is included in the contract documentation in the correct form.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers and their solicitors examine in a records search</h2>
      <p>A body corporate records search is a separate and more detailed document than the disclosure certificate. Buyers commission it independently, typically after going under contract, and it covers the full financial and governance position of the body corporate: meeting minutes, committee decisions, correspondence, insurance certificates, maintenance records, the ten-year sinking fund plan, and any outstanding disputes or legal proceedings.</p>

      <p>Solicitors reviewing a records search are specifically looking for undisclosed special levies, sinking fund shortfalls, unresolved defect disputes, pending litigation involving the body corporate, and whether there are any major capital works planned that are not yet budgeted. A records search that reveals significant issues in any of these areas will almost certainly result in a buyer request to renegotiate price or, in serious cases, termination of the contract.</p>

      <p>As a seller, you cannot control what a records search contains. You can control how prepared your buyers are before they receive it. If you know your building has a pending roof replacement, an underfunded sinking fund, or an ongoing dispute with a neighbouring lot, discuss this with your agent before listing so that the marketing and pricing reflect it accurately and buyers are not blindsided mid-campaign.</p>

